<DOC><DOCNO> AP880809-0034 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0252EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-09 0523</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,500</SECOND><HEAD>Pershing II Motors to Be Destroyed in Texas</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States will begin its firstdestruction of nuclear missile parts under the Intermediate-rangeNuclear Forces treaty on Sept. 8.   The Defense Department, in a brief statement Monday, said thenotice was forwarded to Moscow in accordance with the terms of thetreaty signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.Gorbachev in Washington last year.   Destruction of the solid-fuel rocket motors for the Pershing IImissiles will begin on Sept. 8, ``weather permitting,'' at theLonghorn Army Ammunition Plant near Marshall, Texas, the Pentagonsaid.   The treaty, which became effective earlier this summer, requiresthe superpowers to dismantle and destroy the intermediate-andshorter-range nuclear missiles in their arsenals. The United Stateshas two such types of missiles _ the ground-launched cruise missileand the Pershing II.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Reagan Names Replacement For Pendleton At Civil Rights Commission</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The head of the Leadership Conference on CivilRights is attacking President Reagan's decision to elevate WilliamBarclay Allen to the chairmanship of the U.S. Commission on CivilRights.   ``Regrettably the president has named another right-wingideologue as chairman of the civil rights commission,'' Ralph Neassaid. ``His decision continues to ensure that the commission willlack any credibility and will remain a joke.''   The White House said Monday that Allen, a California educatorand member of the commission since 1987, is Reagan's choice tosucceed Clarence M. Pendleton Jr., who died earlier this year.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>House OKs Bill To Combat Illegal Ivory Imports</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House has approved legislation to bringthe United States into line with an international agreement tocombat illegal trafficking in African elephant ivory.   The measure sent to the Senate by voice vote on Monday wouldprohibit imports into this country of any ivory taken in violationof the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.   That worldwide agreement uses a system of quotas and ivorymarkings in an effort to regulate the international trade in ivoryfrom African elephants, whose numbers have fallen to an estimated700,000 from 1.5 million in 1979.   The bill would ban importation of raw ivory from any nationwithout a native elephant population and would prohibit exportationof raw ivory from the United States.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Biggest US Show of Michelangelo Drawings Planned</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The biggest show of drawings by Michelangeloever seen in the United States will open Oct. 9 at the NationalGallery of Art.   The collection of 46 composition sketches under the title``Michelangelo: Draftsman@Architect'' will include the artist'sgraphic work, including several studies for the Sistine Chapelceiling in Rome.   The ``architect'' portion of the show includes large woodenmodels of the drum and dome of St. Peter's, prepared underMichelangelo's supervision.   This second part of the show is now on view at the CasaBuonarroti in Florence, until Aug. 31. Other parts will be seenhere through Dec. 11 and then go to the Louvre in Paris.   The show in the nation's capital is the only place the exhibitwill be seen in the United States.</TEXT></DOC>